"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984456","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-17","<p>Eligibility for NHS Continuing Healthcare is recorded by National Health Service clinical commissioning group.</p><p> </p><p>In NHS Bexley Clinical Commissioning Group in the first quarter of 2018/19, 224 individuals were eligible for NHS Continuing Healthcare.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984456/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-17T13:13:46.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984456/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984456/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-09","Continuing Care: Bexley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people are in receipt of NHS continuing healthcare in (a) the Bexleyheath and Crayford constituency and (b) Bexley Borough.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","Sir David Evennett","177190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984457","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-15","<p>Once passed, our managed migration regulations will ensure that anyone we move onto Universal Credit, without a change of circumstance, will have their existing benefit entitlement safeguarded. As part of this we will also be providing on-going protection for 500,000 claimants receiving the Severe Disability Premium.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Earlier this month, we announced a new partnership with Citizens Advice and Citizens Advice Scotland to deliver a new approach to Universal Support, initially up to March 2020. Our new partnership will ensure that all those who need to make a claim and need extra support can access it.</p><p> </p><p>Our focus is always on safeguarding claimants and ensuring a smooth transition with uninterrupted support. Our plans, under discussion with stakeholders, already include a mechanism to ensure that, before the existing benefits are stopped, agents will check for evidence of complex needs or vulnerability or disability to safeguard these claimants.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984457/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-15T16:39:24.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984457/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984457/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-09","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what measures are in place to support claimants receiving employment and support allowance in their transition to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","Sir David Evennett","177191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984458","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-15","<p>Department for Work and Pensions staff moving into a case manager role delivering Universal Credit Full Service receive a minimum of 90 hours of job-specific training. New staff joining the Department in this role undertake a minimum of 143 hours of learning. The learning includes guidance and procedures that are based on the Universal Credit regulations.</p><p> </p><p>In all cases, the Department ensures staff are given sufficient on-the-job training to consolidate what they have learnt.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984458/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-15T12:06:33.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984458/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984458/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-09","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what training has been provided to case managers to ensure that they have sufficient knowledge of the universal credit regulations.","false","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","Bexleyheath and Crayford","Sir David Evennett","177192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984459","Treasury","false","2018-10-17","<p>Equitable Life Assurance Society is entirely separate from the Equitable Life Payment Scheme. The Treasury has therefore had no recent meetings with the representatives of Equitable Life on this issue.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984459/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-17T16:13:45.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984459/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984459/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-09","Equitable Life Assurance Society: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions his Department has had with representatives of Equitable Life on payment of the outstanding balance of compensation to policyholders.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","177347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984460","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-17","<p>There have been no Ministerial visits to Greenock Jobcentre. However a number of senior officials from the Department have visited the office since it went live with Universal Credit on 23 November 2016. The last time an official from the Department visited Greenock Jobcentre was on 14 June 2018.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984460/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-17T16:51:36.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984460/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984460/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-09","Universal Credit: Greenock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when the last time was that (a) Ministers and (b) Officials from her Department visited Greenock Jobcentre to discuss the roll-out of Universal Credit.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","177348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984461","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Government has recently announced a comprehensive Rail Review to be independently chaired by Keith Williams. The Review will recommend how the UK Rail sector can deliver better services for passengers, whilst improving its financial sustainability. A definitive, comparable measure demonstrating higher rail operating costs between the UK and Europe is not available. But we do need to ensure that the investment going into the UK’s railways is efficiently used, and costs controlled.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside this, the Government is continuing to use the current periodic review process, which sets Network Rail’s funding and outputs for 2019-24, to robustly challenge Network Rail’s efficiency, including by supporting the strong efficiency challenge on infrastructure costs by the independent Office of Rail and Road.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984461/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-15T16:18:31.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984461/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984461/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-09","Railways: Operating Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the reasons for higher rail operating costs in the UK than in Europe.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","177152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984462","Department for Education","false","2018-10-17","<p>The national curriculum includes substantial content which could be used by teachers as an opportunity to inform pupils about organ, stem cell and blood donation. Pupils are taught about the function of the heart, blood vessels and blood as part of Key Stage 2 science, and about stem cells as part of the Key Stage 4 science. The national curriculum is compulsory in state maintained schools, and is often used as a benchmark by academies.</p><p>In addition, the Government is proposing to introduce compulsory Health Education, alongside Relationships Education and Relationships and Sex Education, and is currently consulting on draft regulations and draft statutory guidance on the subjects. Under the topic of physical health and fitness, the draft guidance sets out that pupils should know the facts about wider issues such as organ and blood donation.</p><p>The consultation on the guidance closes on 7 November.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984462/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-17T15:41:18.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984462/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984462/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-09","Health Education: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if his Department will add stem cell donation to the statutory guidance relating to Health Education for secondary school pupils.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","177301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984463","Department for Education","false","2018-10-15","<p>The further education (FE) sector – including FE colleges – has a different legal status and relationship to the government when compared with schools. FE colleges are private sector institutions, independent of the government. It is for individual FE employers to agree local pay structures with unions, based on local needs.</p><p>The department values all of our teachers and leaders in FE who change lives for the better. Since 2013, we have invested over £120 million in the FE workforce, including investing in workforce development through the independent Education and Training Foundation (ETF).</p><p>Having enough highly-skilled FE teachers in place to deliver high-quality, work-relevant skills training is essential, particularly for the successful delivery of T Levels and apprenticeships. This is why we have committed up to £20 million to help providers, teachers and leaders prepare to deliver T Levels. This includes launching Taking Teaching Further, a £5 million programme to attract industry professionals to teach in FE.</p><p>FE providers help to make sure people have the skills they need to get on in life, which is why we have protected base rate funding for 16 to 19 year olds until 2020. However, we acknowledge that FE faces cost pressures. This is why the department has been actively engaging with the sector to look closely at how we fund providers to ensure that the system supports sustainable, high-quality education. We will be looking carefully at these issues in the Spending Review.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984463/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-15T16:33:38.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984463/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984463/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-09","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the press Association of Colleges' release entitled AoC update on college pay, published in July 2018, if he will he take steps to close the £7000 a year pay disparity between teachers working in further education colleges compared with their counterparts in schools.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","177270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984464","Home Office","false","2018-10-17","<p>The Prime Minister and the Home Secretary have confirmed that in the event of there being no agreement with the EU on the UK’s withdrawal from the EU, all EU citizens and their family members resident in the UK by 29 March 2019 will be able to stay, their rights will be protected and they will be able to live their lives broadly as they do now. Further information will be published in due course.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984464/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-17T15:29:18.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984464/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984464/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-09","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is the Government's policy that the eligibility criteria for the EU Settled Status Scheme as outlined in the EU Settlement Scheme Statement of Intent, published on 21 June 2018, will change in the event that no agreement is reached with the EU on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","177291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984465","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-15","<p>The information requested is not collected in the format requested.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984465/answer",,,,,"177366","2018-10-15T16:38:59.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984465/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984465/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-09","Mental Health Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people aged under 18 in (a)  Dulwich and West Norwood constituency, (b) the London borough of Lambeth and (c) the London borough of Southwark have applied but failed to meet the threshold for child and adolescent mental health services treatment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","177365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984466","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-15","<p>The information requested is not collected in the format requested.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984466/answer",,,,,"177365","2018-10-15T16:38:59.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984466/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984466/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-09","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, by what proportion the number of child and adolescent mental health services referrals have increased in (a) Dulwich and West Norwood constituency and (b) England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","177366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984467","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-15","<p>Where a local National Health Service children and young people’s mental health service rejects a referral, the young person or their carers should be signposted to appropriate support elsewhere, as not all referrals are appropriate for NHS specialist help. We are increasing access to NHS services and aim for an additional 70,000 children and young people a year to receive access to specialist mental health treatment by 2020/21, and we have put the first waiting time standards in place for children and young people’s mental health.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984467/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-15T16:39:47.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984467/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984467/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-09","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to page 21 of the Education Policy Institute's report, Access to children and young people's mental health services - 2018, published in October 2018, if he will make an assessment of the implications for policies of the finding that there was no or limited follow-up involving the CAMHS providers of referrals including cases involving self harm.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","177367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984468","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-10-15","<p>The Housing Revenue Account borrowing cap for local authorities will be removed as soon as possible, with further detail confirmed in the Budget.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984468/answer",,,,,,"2018-10-15T16:16:10.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984468/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/984468/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-09","Housing Revenue Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for the removal of the Housing Revenue Account borrowing cap for local authorities.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","177368"
